Currently all labels are converted to lower-case after entering. This is a problem with some languages other than english. 

In the german language for example, all substantives start with a capital character. Substantives are very often used as labels. So whenever someone uses german substantives as labels, the resulting list of labels looks just wrong. At least one customer considers this as a bug instead of just an improvement.

Since Java provides case-agnostic string search functions, it is technically not a big problem to fix.

Adaptavist rightly so reported:

On line 91 of comments.vmd from confluence 3.0 the following code is used.

{code}
            #if ( $threadComments && $replyToComment == $comment.id && $permissionCheckDispatcher.isPermitted("/pages/doaddcomment.action?pageId=$page.id") && $action.isPrintableVersion()==false )
{code}

it would be arguably better to explicitly use $action as used elsewhere in the comments.vmd, eg:
{code}
            #if ( $action.threadComments && $action.replyToComment == $comment.id && $permissionCheckDispatcher.isPermitted("/pages/doaddcomment.action?pageId=$page.id") && $action.isPrintableVersion()==false )
{code}

The reason I noticed this is because commenting broke in 3.0 with builder, and I had to add code in to pull those variables off the action (comments in builder are rendered from a macro, not in the decorator)

I don't actually need this fixing since I've worked around it, and I doubt anyone else will experience the same problem because nobody else is as crazy as we are, however it would seem to make sense to follow the same pattern as used elsewhere in the comments.vmd code.

Feel free to close this issue at will, I'm just offering a suggestion.

